article.description:
Richard Roby overcame a miserable day of
shooting to score 17 points and Martane Freeman added 13 points as
Colorado held off Texas Tech 66-64 on Saturday.
article.headline: No. 25 Colorado holds off Texas Tech at home
article.linkText: No. 25 Colorado holds off Texas Tech at home
article.story: BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- Colorado players saw Texas Tech at its worst in the first half and expected a better showing from the Red Raiders in the second half. They got it. Texas Tech shot 28 percent in the first half, but it took a flurry of free throws at the end for Colorado (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today; unranked AP) to hold on to a 66-64 victory over Texas Tech on Saturday. "They struggled on offense, that's for sure in the first half, but we never saw any of them hang their heads," said Colorado point guard Marcus Hall, who had 13 points, but missed two free throws with six seconds left to give the Red Raiders a chance to win. "We knew they would come back." Colorado (16-5, 6-4 Big 12) wasn't much better, hitting 9-of-33 shots in the first period. And it didn't get much better for leading scorer Richard Roby, who struggled for his 17 points on 3-for-11 shooting but was 10-for-11 from the free throw line in helping Colorado snap a two-game losing streak. Jarrius Jackson led Texas Tech (12-12, 4-6) with 18 points. Martin Zeno had 17 as the Red Raiders remained winless in five conference road games. The Red Raiders missed their first eight shots and had four turnovers to start the game before Darryl Dora buried a 3-pointer with 14:23 left. By then Andy Osborn had hit two 3-pointers and the Buffaloes led 9-3. "We had to remind our team not to take anything for granted and that a win wouldn't come easy," Colorado coach Ricardo Patton said. "It was going to be a hard-fought game and it was going to be a 40-minute contest." Roby's first points of the game came on a rebound basket and layup midway through the half to make it 22-8, but the Red Raiders went on a 9-0 run. Two free throws each by Dora and Zeno cut it to 25-23. Martane Freeman, who finished with 13 points, came off the bench to have a layup and 3-pointer in the last 2:11 to make it 30-25 at the break. "I am disappointed by the way we started," Texas Tech coach Bob Knight said. "Colorado is such a good team that it's difficult to come back on them." But they did. Osborn's 3-pointer put Colorado up by six early in the second half, but two baskets off inside moves by Jackson got the Red Raiders as close as 41-39 with 11:35 left. Two unforced turnovers by Colorado led to 3-pointers by Zeno and Dora, and Texas Tech took its first lead, 46-45. Roby broke a 50-50 tie with a 3-pointer and hit two free throws with 5:41 remaining to put the Buffaloes ahead 55-50, but Jon Plefka's 3-pointer and Zeno's short jumper got the Red Raiders within 57-55 with 3:43 left. Jackson had eight points the rest of the way, but Colorado countered with nine free throws, including three by Roby. The Buffaloes missed only two free throws over the final stretch, both by Hall with 5.8 seconds left. "Before Hall went to the line, coach had two pieces of advice for us," Roby said. "Don't let Jackson get an open look, and get the rebound." Jackson found just enough of a seam to get off an off-balance shot before the buzzer from beyond the 3-point arc, but the ball caught the front of the rim and bounded out.
